# ============================================================
# .cursorrules ‚Äî PrivaCI Python Development Standards
# ============================================================
# These rules apply to all Python code in this repository.
# The AI assistant must follow every rule below when writing,
# editing, or reviewing code. No exceptions without explicit
# inline justification from the developer.
# ============================================================


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# SECTION 1: PYTHON BEST PRACTICES
# ------------------------------------------------------------

## Language & Runtime
- Target Python 3.12+ exclusively. Use modern language features ‚Äî no legacy compatibility shims.
- Every function, method, and class attribute MUST have type hints (PEP 484/526).
- Use `from __future__ import annotations` at the top of every module for forward references.
- Prefer `pathlib.Path` over `os.path` for all filesystem operations.
- Use f-strings for all string formatting. Never use `.format()` or `%` formatting.
- Use `dataclasses` or `pydantic.BaseModel` for structured data. Never use raw dicts as
  function return types when the shape is known.

## Control Flow & Structure
- Maximum function length: 40 lines. If a function exceeds this, decompose it.
- Maximum file length: 400 lines. Split modules when approaching this limit.
- Maximum cyclomatic complexity: 8 per function. Simplify nested conditionals with early returns.
- Avoid deeply nested code. Prefer guard clauses (early returns) over nested if/else pyramids.
- Never use mutable default arguments (e.g., `def foo(items: list = [])`).
  Use `None` as default and initialize inside the function body.
- Use list/dict/set comprehensions for simple transforms. Use explicit `for` loops
  when logic is complex enough to need explanation.
- Prefer `any()` and `all()` over manual loop accumulators for boolean checks.

## Classes & Objects
- Use `__slots__` on performance-critical or frequently-instantiated classes.
- Prefer composition over inheritance. Limit class inheritance depth to 2.
- Abstract base classes must use `abc.ABC` and `@abstractmethod`.
- Use `@property` for computed attributes. Never expose internal state directly.
- Override `__repr__` on all domain model classes. It must show enough to debug.

## Error Handling
- Never use bare `except:` or `except Exception:` without logging the exception first.
- Define custom exception classes per module. Inherit from a base `PrivaCIError`.
- Always use context managers (`with`) for file handles, DB connections, and network sockets.
- Catch the narrowest possible exception type. Never silence errors silently.
- On fatal errors, log then raise ‚Äî never swallow and continue.

## Async
- Use `asyncio` for all I/O-bound operations (DB reads/writes, HTTP calls, file streaming).
- Never call blocking I/O inside an async function. Use `asyncio.to_thread()` for
  blocking libraries that lack async support.
- Prefer `asyncio.gather()` for concurrent tasks over sequential `await` chains.

## Logging
- Use the `logging` module exclusively. Never use `print()` in production code paths.
- Logger instances must be module-level: `logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)`.
- Log levels: DEBUG for trace/iteration detail, INFO for lifecycle events,
  WARNING for recoverable issues, ERROR for failures, CRITICAL for unrecoverable state.
- Every log message at WARNING or above must include structured context
  (e.g., `logger.error("Mask run failed", extra={"table": table_name, "row": row_id})`).
- Never log raw PII values. Truncate or redact sensitive fields before logging.

## Dependencies
- All dependencies must be pinned to exact versions in `requirements.txt`.
  Use `pip-compile` (pip-tools) to generate and lock the dependency tree.
- Separate `requirements.txt` (production) from `requirements-dev.txt` (test/lint/format).
- Before adding a new dependency, confirm it is actively maintained and has no
  known critical CVEs. Document the justification in a comment above the import.


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# SECTION 2: TESTING
# ------------------------------------------------------------

## Framework & Structure
- All tests use `pytest`. No `unittest.TestCase` classes unless wrapping legacy code.
- Test files live in a `/tests` directory at the project root, mirroring the `src/` structure.
  Example: `src/masking/engine.py` ‚Üí `tests/masking/test_engine.py`.
- Test file names are prefixed with `test_`. Test function names are prefixed with `test_`.
- Test class names are prefixed with `Test` (e.g., `TestMaskingEngine`).

## Coverage Requirements
- Minimum test coverage: 85% overall, 100% for security-critical modules
  (`src/masking/`, `src/config/`, `src/billing/`).
- Run coverage with: `pytest --cov=src --cov-report=term-missing --cov-fail-under=85`.
- Every new function or method MUST have at least one positive test and one negative/edge test.

## Test Design Patterns
- Follow strict Arrange-Act-Assert (AAA) structure in every test, separated by blank lines.
  ```python
  def test_email_is_masked():
      # Arrange
      row = {"email": "john@acme.com"}
      masker = EmailMasker(salt="test-salt")

      # Act
      result = masker.mask(row)

      # Assert
      assert result["email"] != "john@acme.com"
      assert "@" in result["email"]
  ```
- Use `@pytest.mark.parametrize` for any test covering multiple input variants.
  Never copy-paste test functions with minor input changes.
- Use `pytest.fixture` for all shared setup (DB connections, config objects, temp files).
  Fixtures must be scoped appropriately: `function` (default), `module`, or `session`.
- Use `pytest-mock` (`mocker` fixture) for all mocking. Never monkey-patch directly.
- Integration tests that touch real DB connections must be marked `@pytest.mark.integration`
  and excluded from default runs: `pytest -m "not integration"`.

## What Must Be Tested
- All masking logic: verify original value is not present in output.
- Referential integrity: same input + same salt always produces same output.
- Edge cases: null/None values, empty strings, Unicode, very long strings (>10k chars).
- Schema discovery: invalid connection strings, missing tables, permission errors.
- Config parser: malformed YAML, missing required fields, unknown action types.
- Billing heartbeat: network failure simulation, retry behavior, graceful degradation.

## Test Data
- Never use real PII in test fixtures, even synthetic-looking real data.
- Define all test constants in `tests/fixtures/constants.py`. No magic strings inline.
- Use `faker` library to generate realistic test data in fixtures, seeded for repeatability:
  `Faker().seed_instance(42)`.
- Database fixtures use `pytest-postgresql` or a local Docker Compose service.
  Never point tests at a shared or production database.


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# SECTION 3: SECURITY
# ------------------------------------------------------------

## Secrets & Credentials
- Zero hardcoded secrets, tokens, passwords, salts, or connection strings anywhere in code.
  This includes test files, fixtures, and scripts.
- All secrets are read exclusively from environment variables via `os.environ` or `python-dotenv`.
- Provide a `.env.example` file with dummy values and clear comments for every required variable.
- Never commit `.env` files. Verify `.gitignore` excludes `.env`, `*.pem`, `*.key`, `*.p12`.
- Salt values (`ANONYMIZATION_SALT`) must be minimum 32 characters. Validate length on boot.

## Input Validation
- Validate and sanitize all external inputs before processing: DB connection strings,
  YAML config values, column names, table names, and any user-provided strings.
- Use `pydantic.BaseModel` with strict field validators for all config parsing.
  Reject unknown fields with `model_config = ConfigDict(extra="forbid")`.
- Never construct SQL strings via string concatenation. Always use parameterized queries
  or ORM query builders. This is non-negotiable.
- Treat all data read from source databases as untrusted. Validate types before
  passing values into masking functions.

## Data Handling
- PII values must never appear in logs, error messages, stack traces, or exception text.
  Mask or truncate before any logging call.
- Never write intermediate masked data to disk. All processing occurs in memory.
- DB connection objects must be closed in `finally` blocks or via context managers.
  No connection leaks.
- Use `secrets` module (not `random`) for any cryptographic or security-sensitive
  random value generation.

## Dependency Security
- Run `pip-audit` as part of CI on every push. Fail the build on any known critical CVE.
- Pin all transitive dependencies. Never use unpinned ranges (e.g., `requests>=2.0`)
  in production requirements.
- Review the changelog of any dependency before version bumps in security-sensitive
  areas of the codebase.

## Container Security
- The Docker image must run as a non-root user. Define `USER privaci` in the Dockerfile.
- Use a minimal base image (`python:3.11-slim`). No full `python:3.11` base in production.
- Never bake secrets into the Docker image. All secrets are environment variables at runtime.
- Expose no network ports in the container unless explicitly required.


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# SECTION 4: FORMATTING & CODE STYLE
# ------------------------------------------------------------

## Formatter
- All code is formatted with `black` using default settings (line length 88).
- Run: `black src/ tests/`
- Black is non-negotiable. Do not manually reformat code that black would reformat.

## Import Ordering
- Imports are sorted with `isort` configured to be black-compatible:
  `isort --profile black src/ tests/`
- Import order: standard library ‚Üí third-party ‚Üí local. Separated by blank lines.
  ```python
  from __future__ import annotations

  import asyncio
  import logging
  from pathlib import Path

  import pydantic
  import yaml

  from privaci.masking.engine import MaskingEngine
  from privaci.config import MaskConfig
  ```
- Never use wildcard imports (`from module import *`).
- Avoid importing entire modules when only one function is needed.

## Linting
- All code must pass `ruff` with the following rule sets enabled: `E, F, W, I, N, UP, S, B, A`.
  Run: `ruff check src/ tests/`
- No `# noqa` suppression comments without an inline explanation of why.
- No unused imports, unused variables, or unreachable code.

## Naming Conventions
- Variables and functions: `snake_case`
- Classes: `PascalCase`
- Constants: `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE`, defined at module level
- Private methods/attributes: single leading underscore `_method_name`
- "Protected" from subclass access: double leading underscore `__method_name` (use sparingly)
- Boolean variables and functions: prefix with `is_`, `has_`, `should_`, `can_`
  (e.g., `is_masked`, `has_pii`, `should_skip_table`)

## General Style Rules
- Maximum line length: 88 characters (black default).
- No trailing whitespace. No blank lines at end of file. Files end with a single newline.
- Use explicit `True`/`False` comparisons only when the type is not obviously boolean.
  Prefer `if value:` over `if value == True:`.
- Prefer `is None` / `is not None` over `== None` / `!= None`.
- Unpack tuples explicitly: `first, second = get_pair()` not `result = get_pair(); result[0]`.


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# SECTION 5: COMMENTS
# ------------------------------------------------------------

## When to Comment
- Comments explain WHY, not WHAT. Code explains what. Comments explain intent,
  constraints, trade-offs, and decisions that aren't obvious from reading the code.
- Every non-trivial algorithm must have a prose comment before it explaining the approach.
- Every `# type: ignore` must have an inline comment explaining why it was necessary.
- Every `TODO` must include the author's initials and a GitHub issue number:
  `# TODO(jd): replace with async version ‚Äî see #42`
- Every `FIXME` is a bug and must have a linked issue before the PR is merged.
- Every `HACK` or `WORKAROUND` comment must describe the root cause and the conditions
  under which it can be removed.

## What NOT to Comment
- Do not comment obvious code: `# increment counter` above `count += 1` is noise.
- Do not leave commented-out code in the codebase. Use git history instead.
- Do not write comments that restate the function signature. That's what docstrings are for.

## Inline Comment Style
- Inline comments use two spaces before `#` and one space after: `value = mask(x)  # deterministic`
- Keep inline comments to one line. Multi-line explanations belong above the block.


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# SECTION 6: DOCUMENTATION
# ------------------------------------------------------------

## Docstring Standard: Google Style
- Every public module, class, function, and method must have a Google-style docstring.
- Private functions (`_prefixed`) should have docstrings when their behavior is non-obvious.
- Docstrings use triple double-quotes `"""`. Never single-quote docstrings.

### Module Docstring (top of every file)
```python
"""Schema discovery module for PrivaCI.

Queries PostgreSQL system catalogs to extract table structure, column metadata,
primary key constraints, and foreign key relationships. Results feed the
streaming engine and masking pipeline.
"""
```

### Function / Method Docstring
```python
def mask_email(value: str, salt: str) -> str:
    """Generate a deterministic fake email from a real email address.

    Hashes the original value with the provided salt to produce a stable
    seed, then selects a fake name and domain from built-in libraries.
    The same input always produces the same output for a given salt.

    Args:
        value: The original email address to mask. Must be a valid RFC 5321
            email string. Empty strings return an empty string unchanged.
        salt: The anonymization salt from ANONYMIZATION_SALT env variable.
            Must be at least 32 characters.

    Returns:
        A realistic-looking fake email string (e.g., "alex.rivera@fakedom.net").
        Preserves the general structure (local@domain) of the original.

    Raises:
        ValueError: If salt is fewer than 32 characters.
        MaskingError: If the fake library fails to generate a value after
            3 retry attempts.

    Example:
        >>> mask_email("john@acme.com", salt="super-secret-salt-12345678901234")
        'alex.rivera@fakedom.net'
    """
```

### Class Docstring
```python
class MaskingEngine:
    """Orchestrates the three-tier masking pipeline for a single table.

    Coordinates Regex rules (Level 1), SpaCy NER (Level 2), and optional
    LLM refinement (Level 3) based on the provided MaskConfig. Stateless
    between rows ‚Äî all state is passed in via constructor arguments.

    Attributes:
        config: The validated masking configuration for this table.
        salt: The global anonymization salt used for deterministic faking.
        ner_model: The loaded SpaCy NLP model, or None if Level 2 is disabled.

    Example:
        >>> engine = MaskingEngine(config=table_config, salt="my-salt")
        >>> masked_row = engine.process_row({"email": "john@acme.com"})
    """
```

## README Standards
- Every module directory must contain a `README.md` explaining:
  - What the module does (one paragraph)
  - Public API surface (key classes and functions)
  - Configuration options
  - Example usage
- The project root `README.md` must contain:
  - One-paragraph product description
  - Prerequisites (Python version, Docker, env variables)
  - Quickstart (copy-pasteable commands to run locally)
  - Link to full docs

## Changelog
- Maintain a `CHANGELOG.md` in the project root following Keep a Changelog format.
- Every PR that changes behavior (not just refactors or tests) must add an entry
  under `[Unreleased]` in the appropriate category: Added, Changed, Deprecated,
  Removed, Fixed, Security.

## Architecture Decision Records (ADRs)
- Significant architectural decisions (choice of library, schema design, licensing,
  billing model) must be documented in `/docs/adr/` as numbered markdown files.
  Format: `0001-use-bsl-license.md`, `0002-cursor-based-pagination.md`.
- ADR template:
  ```
  # ADR-NNNN: Title

  ## Status
  Accepted | Proposed | Deprecated

  ## Context
  What situation forced this decision?

  ## Decision
  What was decided?

  ## Consequences
  What are the trade-offs and implications?
  ```


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# SECTION 7: CI/CD & TOOLING INTEGRATION
# ------------------------------------------------------------

## Pre-commit Hooks (required in every contributor's environment)
Run `pre-commit install` and `pre-commit install --hook-type commit-msg` after
cloning. The following hooks run on every commit:
- `black` ‚Äî formatting
- `isort` ‚Äî import ordering
- `ruff` ‚Äî linting
- `pip-audit` ‚Äî dependency vulnerability scan
- Custom hook: reject any file containing `TODO` without an issue number
- Custom hook: public-repo language guard (ADR-0007; commit-msg + staged paths)
- Custom hook: capability registry integrity when `src/`, `tests/`, or
  `scripts/capability_test/` change ‚Äî new unit test files must be registered in
  `scripts/capability_test/registry.py`
- Custom hook: `./scripts/capability-test-suite.sh quick` on the same paths
  (public-unit only when `../privaci-commercial` is absent)
- Custom hook: `./scripts/ci-local.sh` on `src/`, `tests/`, or `scripts/`
  (full CI parity ‚Äî **required before commit**; also runs on pre-push)

When adding a user-facing capability, register it in
`scripts/capability_test/registry.py` before commit. See
`.cursor/rules/capability-test-registry.mdc` and
`.cursor/rules/ci-before-commit.mdc`.

## CI Pipeline Gates (all must pass before merge)
- `black --check src/ tests/`
- `isort --check-only --profile black src/ tests/`
- `ruff check src/ tests/`
- `pytest --cov=src --cov-fail-under=85 -m "not integration"`
- `pip-audit --requirement requirements.txt`
- `mypy src/ --strict`

## Type Checking
- Run `mypy src/ --strict` with zero errors as a CI gate.
- Never suppress mypy errors with `# type: ignore` without an inline comment
  explaining what the type system cannot express and why.
- All third-party libraries must have stubs (`types-*` packages) or be listed
  in `mypy.ini` under `[[mypy-library_name]]` with `ignore_missing_imports = True`.


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# SECTION 8: AI ASSISTANT BEHAVIOUR (CURSOR-SPECIFIC)
# ------------------------------------------------------------

## When Writing New Code
- Always add type hints. Do not omit them for "brevity".
- Always write the docstring before implementing the function body.
- Always suggest a test file path alongside new production code.
- If a function would exceed 40 lines, decompose it and explain the split.
- If a security-sensitive operation is involved (DB query, file write, external call),
  add a `# SECURITY:` comment explaining the threat model consideration.

## Git workflow (branch-first)
- **Never push feature, fix, docs, or CI changes directly to `main`.** Create a
  branch (`feat/`, `fix/`, `chore/`, `docs/`), run CI gates locally, push the
  branch, and open a PR ‚Äî unless the user explicitly requests a direct `main` push
  or a release tag cut.
- **Before every commit**, run `./scripts/ci-local.sh` and do not commit until
  it exits 0. See `.cursor/rules/ci-before-commit.mdc`. If the user asks to
  commit, run ci-local in the same turn first ‚Äî never skip or defer to the user.
- Before every push, ci-local must already have passed on the commits being pushed.
- Release tags (`v*`) are cut on `main` only after merge, when the user requests a
  release.

## When Editing Existing Code
- Do not remove or alter existing docstrings unless the behavior actually changed.
- Do not reformat code outside the directly edited lines (black handles formatting).
- If a change introduces a new dependency, flag it explicitly and explain why an
  existing dependency cannot serve the same purpose.

## What the Assistant Must Never Do
- Never use "commercial hooks/entitlement/metering" in public-repo commit messages,
  CHANGELOG entries, release notes, or engine implementation comments when describing
  ``privaci.contracts`` lifecycle wiring ‚Äî say **plugin contract** / **UsageMeter
  lifecycle** instead (ADR-0007; see ``.cursor/rules/public-repo-language.mdc``).
- Never generate code that logs raw PII values.
- Never generate hardcoded credentials, salts, or tokens, even as placeholders.
  Use environment variable references and a comment indicating what is expected.
- Never use `eval()`, `exec()`, or `__import__()` dynamically.
- Never generate SQL queries via string concatenation.
- Never suppress test failures or mock away the system under test itself.
- Never use `time.sleep()` in async code. Use `asyncio.sleep()`.
